Financial report for the financial year July 2019- June 2020 was released 20 August[1]. For the first half of this year Qantas lost 50%+ of it's passengers compared to the previous year (approximately 12 million 2019-20 to 27 million 2018-19). Considering that air traffic was pretty normal the first 2+ months of the year the impact of the Covid-19 pandemic is closer to a 75% decline in passenger numbers. There is simply no way Qantas will have even close to 16 million passengers the second half of 2020.

Qantas has mothballed its International fleet in a three-year plan to restructure its business as 90% of business has evaporated due to the onset of Covid-19. The airline does have a domestic division that was hoping to retain 40% of its business within closed frontiers (possibly including Covid-19 free New Zealand) that would have amounted to 4.4 million passenger flights over a six-month period, (2019 had 22million over 12-month period). However, this has been thwarted by either a Coronavirus spike (1st Wave) or the onset of a second wave, especially in Melbourne , Victoria and the States have been closing their borders to interstate travellers placing further pressure on the travel industry.

"Australia reported a record 15 deaths from COVID-19 on Wednesday, all in Victoria state, which was preparing to close much of its economy to control a second wave of infection that threatens to spread across the country ... The second-most populous state in Australia reported a record rise of 725 new COVID-19 cases despite having reimposed a lockdown on Melbourne, the state capital with a population of 5 million people, four weeks ago ... In northeastern Queensland state, Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk said travelers from New South Wales and the capital Canberra would be barred from Saturday. The state is already closed to Victorians." https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-australia/australia-suffers-record-coronavirus-deaths-triggering-tighter-curbs-idUSKCN251053

May was down over 90% year-on-year [1] for domestic values and an even higher drop (+98%) for international [2]. While there has been a recent increase in cases [3,4], these seem to be contained with local lockdown measures, and from Vox [4], "the “highs” Australia is seeing right now are basically what some of America’s more well-off states are seeing on a good day." This means, though, there will be continued vigilance and a continued low travel numbers.

There are ~26 weeks in the second half of 2020. According to CNN Business, Qantas "is still seeing increasing demand for travel within Australia as local restrictions are slowly lifted. Qantas Group's domestic passenger numbers within the country doubled this week to 64,000 people" [1]. My guess is that this figure is likely to either stay steady or increase given Australia's low case numbers [2] and the fact that most international flights for the rest of the year have been cancelled (so Australians are likely to vacation/travel more within the country via domestic flights) [3]. This implies that there will be at least 1,664,000 passengers (64,000 passengers last week * 26 weeks) — which is still an order of magnitude below 16 million!

Currently, Qantas has halted all international flights at least till the end of July 2020 — https://www.qantas.com/au/en/travel-info/travel-updates/coronavirus/qantas-international-network-changes.html Local transmission of COVID in Australia is now virtually extinct and nearly all cases are incoming international travellers. This would suggest that the international border is not likely to open anytime soon. But there is much talk of the economic need for tourism and international students, which would apply pressure to open the border sooner rather than later. It seems logical the government will opt for a staged re-opening of the border through the second half of 2020, after July. This leaves a maximum of 5 months, which at H2 2020 rates would equate to 24m passengers. However, it is also likely that a significant proportion of cancelled H1 trips (business and tourism) may be taken in the second half of the year. With all these considerations in mind, the likely figure will almost certainly be less than 24m. The question is: by how much? And the will depend most heavily on the government's schedule for re-opening the border. Given that the biggest factor influencing that decision is the progress of COVID worldwide, and that that doesn't look like slowing down anytime soon, I have wagered that the border will be opened slowly and selectively, which favours the lower figure.

Quanta's carries around 55 million passengers per year. Maybe this could be split as 25 million in the first half and 30 million in the second half.

Expect slow reintroduction of international flights. Aus-NZ flights may reopen earlier than to other destinations, but I expect this would not result in large passenger numbers, and would be split with AirNZ. Expect domestic flights to increase from current numbers but still remain down from previous levels due to suppressed business activity and spending, higher unemployment resulting in fewer holiday travellers. On the other hand, Qantas' main domestic rival, Virgin, is in administration and so expect Qantas to pick up a larger slice of the domestic market.

UPDATED: In a typical year, more than 28 million passengers would likely be carried. Qantas Airways Limited has demonstrated growth in passengers carried, seats available, and revenue from 2014 to 2019. This includes carrying 48,776,000 passengers in 2014; 52,681,000 in 2016; and 55,273,000 in 2018 according to tables in the 2018 Annual Report. However, the COVID-19 pandemic has halted significant portions of air travel. Two trends used to forecast the impact this will have on the total passengers carried in the second half of the year include Australia's recovery from COVID-19 and Qantas' domestic flights. Approximately four months passed in China from the first cases until a day without new cases and it continues to see less than 100 to 200 new cases per day. Like other countries, China has restricted international travel. As a result it is likely that Australia will see major recovery by July, although international travel limits may remain in place. Qantas has suspended nearly all international flights and cut domestic capacity by 60% to deal with the current drop in demand for flights. On the other hand, Qantas is financially stable, has a broad domestic network, and expects to see pent up demand after COVID-19. Domestic flights alone may bring Qantas 12 to 13 million passengers at 80% of domestic capacity because Qantas carried over 32 million passengers on domestic flights in 2019.

I think question is mostly about when and how the demand for the airline is going to recover from covid-19. Qantas displayed 2 solid years, without much change, and there is not much reason for crazy change in the supply of Qantas. The government provided a solid package of about $A 1 billion to airlines, which focused on the big airlines such as Qantas and therefore I feel that despite the cuts and change to operations they had to make, the airline will not be significantly weakened in the short run. Now for the demand side. Most articles I have read have given a timeline of roughly 4-7 months for demand to increase again. This is much more global and severe than SARS which took a bit less time than this for demand of tourism to recover in Asia. An important factor is that Qantas is focused on international air, which means that it will be badly hit in demand. However, its data books show that roughly 40% of its flights are to and from Asia, which has recovered much more quickly and effectively from the virus. This suggests that this portion of passengers will not change much. However for its flights elsewhere, it will take a siginficant amount of time for demand to recover.
